<paper id="1514827773"><title>Classification of Medical Images Using Local Representations</title><year>2002</year><authors><author org="Universidad Politécnica de valencia" id="2158227529">Roberto Paredes</author><author org="RWTH Aachen" id="2145628901">Daniel Keysers</author><author org="RWTH Aachen" id="2107603943">Thomas Martin Lehmann</author><author org="RWTH Aachen" id="2296843404">Berthold B. Wein</author><author org="RWTH Aachen" id="2293758362">Hermann Ney</author><author org="Universidad Politécnica de valencia" id="2151398381">Enrique Vidal</author></authors><n_citation>23</n_citation><doc_type /><references><reference>1525596811</reference><reference>1589246422</reference><reference>1590869108</reference><reference>1673641227</reference><reference>1970434578</reference><reference>2015206503</reference><reference>2124087378</reference><reference>2427881153</reference></references><venue id="" type="">Bildverarbeitung f&amp;uuml;r die Medizin</venue><doi>10.1007/978-3-642-55983-9_39</doi><keywords><keyword weight="0.46754">Computer vision</keyword><keyword weight="0.74051">Automatic image annotation</keyword><keyword weight="0.46495">Pattern recognition</keyword><keyword weight="0.41966">Computer science</keyword><keyword weight="0.74049">Image retrieval</keyword><keyword weight="0.59532">Image analysis</keyword><keyword weight="0.0">Artificial intelligence</keyword><keyword weight="0.0">Image database</keyword><keyword weight="0.70951">Visual Word</keyword></keywords><publisher>Springer, Berlin, Heidelberg</publisher><abstract>In medical image retrieval, the images are usually subject to a large range of variability. In order to classify medical images, we therefore propose the use of local representations, which are small square windows taken from the images. This approach is combined with a fast approximate k-nearest neighbor technique and yields state-of-the-art results on a medical image database of 1617 images.</abstract></paper>